=E2=80=9CWe find it difficult to come up with a realistic scenario where th=
ere=E2=80=99s residual value for First Republic common equity holders,=E2=
=80=9D Wedbush analyst David Chiaverini wrote in a note to clients. Chiaver=
ini downgraded the stock to neutral, cutting his price target to $5 from $1=
40.
Atlantic Equities John Heagerty also downgraded First Republic to neutral c=
iting =E2=80=9Cunprecedented uncertainty=E2=80=9D surrounding the Californi=
a lender. He said a return to prior leverage ratios for the bank =E2=80=9Cm=
ay well necessitate a capital raise.=E2=80=9D

But the goal here is not really to save First Republic common equity holder=
s. The goal is to save confidence in the system. (=E2=80=9CIts shares fell =
sharply on Friday morning after the bank had said it would cancel its divid=
end on Thursday,=E2=80=9D  reported the New York Times, which is honestly a=
 funny sentence: If there is any question about a bank=E2=80=99s ability to=
 pay its depositors, of course it should not pay a dividend to its sharehol=
ders!
  [7]
)
Let=E2=80=99s talk about a few contrasts. Silicon Valley Bank   failed last=
 week because, to oversimplify slightly, its interconnected network of tech=
-startup and venture-capitalist depositors all worked themselves into a pan=
ic and rushed to withdraw money all at once, then tweeted indignantly about=
 how they were justified in doing that and how it was all the Fed=E2=80=99s=
 fault. It=C2=A0was=C2=A0individually rational for each depositor to take i=
ts money out and avoid exposure to SVB, but the collective result was quite=
 bad=C2=A0for SVB and for the banking system and for the VCs and startups t=
hemselves. Silicon Valley Bank=E2=80=99s Silicon Valley customers, it turne=
d out, were individually rational but unable to act cooperatively in a mutu=
ally beneficial way; in the prisoners=E2=80=99 dilemma of a bank run, they =
all chose to defect.=C2=A0
Banking analyst Dan Davies was  scathing on Twitter, writing about the Firs=
t Republic rescue:
When you tell 11 bankers that someone is in trouble, seems that they ask "h=
ow can we help". Just don't try that with effective altruists eh.
And:
I would also guess that there was no one in that room at the fed saying "we=
ll actually running on the bank is the rational thing to do actually"
Ben Thompson was possibly even more scathing  at Stratechery:
I assumed that Silicon Valley broadly was in the business of taking care of=
 their own. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0[But] the bank run that resulted made it clear t=
hat everyone, from venture capitalists to the startups they advised, were s=
olely concerned about their own welfare, not about the ecosystem as a whole=
.
Thompson=E2=80=99s argument in that post is that Silicon Valley used to be =
an=C2=A0iterated game among repeat players: Venture capitalists had long ca=
reers and made many investments and would benefit way more from building a =
good reputation and helping the overall startup ecosystem than they would b=
y maximizing their winnings on any one deal. But, he argues, as startup exi=
ts and venture funds have gotten bigger, =E2=80=9Csuccess became less about=
 a series of victories and more about going big or going home,=E2=80=9D and=
 that cooperative ethos has weakened.
It is funny to think of tech founders and venture capitalists as creatures =
of myopic=C2=A0self-interest, while=C2=A0bank CEOs=C2=A0are the generous al=
truists, but the point is=C2=A0the bankers don=E2=80=99t have a choice. Ban=
king is a necessarily social business, banks are interconnected, and=C2=A0t=
he best and biggest bank is only as good as confidence in the broad banking=
 system. You can=E2=80=99t =E2=80=9Cgo big or go home=E2=80=9D; even Jamie =
Dimon has to care about the health of his less competent competitors. If yo=
u blitzscale the best food-delivery startup and drive all the other food-de=
livery startups out of business, you win; if you build the best bank and ot=
her banks start going out of business, that is a mixed bag, at best,=C2=A0f=
or you.
The other contrast I want to point to is=C2=A0crypto. Crypto is a social co=
nstruct like banking, but it is far more=C2=A0obviously=C2=A0socially const=
ructed. It=E2=80=99s=C2=A0all just stuff that people made up in the last de=
cade or so. It relies even more on confidence, and that confidence is shaki=
er.=C2=A0When a bunch of crypto firms went bust last summer, Sam Bankman-Fr=
ied=E2=80=99s crypto exchange FTX, and his crypto trading firm Alameda Rese=
arch, often ended up rescuing them. Bankman-Fried got the nickname =E2=80=
=9CJPEG Morgan,=E2=80=9D referencing J. Pierpont Morgan=E2=80=99s own habit=
 of rescuing troubled banks to avert panic. This was, I think, smart of him=
; it was what a good banker would do.=C2=A0Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s own weal=
th was very highly leveraged to overall confidence in the crypto ecosystem,=
 so it was better for him to support failing competitors =E2=80=94=C2=A0and=
 prop up that confidence =E2=80=94=C2=A0than it would be to let them fail. =
He was in a cooperative confidence game, and he acted like it.
Of course =E2=80=9Cconfidence game=E2=80=9D is also a=C2=A0bad thing, and F=
TX and Alameda went bust themselves in November, which puts Bankman-Fried=
=E2=80=99s rescues=C2=A0in a worse light: It is good to prop up confidence =
in a socially beneficial system that runs on=C2=A0confidence, but bad to pr=
op up confidence in a fraud. And while banking is a matter of confidence in=
 a long-standing, deeply socially embedded system that finances lots of peo=
ple=E2=80=99s real-world houses and businesses, crypto exchanges are=C2=A0=
=E2=80=A6=C2=A0not that. If you are a bank and there is a run on the bank, =
you will have to sell your mortgage loans and Treasury bonds and whatever, =
and you will lose money selling them at fire-sale prices, and you might bec=
ome insolvent and deposits might be at risk and the FDIC and the Fed=C2=A0m=
ight have to step in. But if you are a crypto bank and there is a run on th=
e bank, you will have to sell=C2=A0some   magic beans you made up, and you =
will sell them=C2=A0for zero dollars, and you will become=C2=A0extremely=C2=
=A0insolvent and your customers might get pennies on the dollar, and the FD=
