<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Banking is a confidence trick. You put money i=
n the bank today because you are confident you can take it out tomorrow; to=
 you, a dollar that you have deposited in the bank is just as good =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0just as much <em>money </em>=E2=80=94 as a dollar bill in your wal=
let. If you show up at the ATM at any time of day or night, you expect it t=
o give you your dollars. But the bank doesn=E2=80=99t just put your dollars=
 in a box and wait for you to take them out; the bank uses its depositors=
=E2=80=99 money to make loans or buy bonds, and just keeps a little bit aro=
und for people who need cash. If everyone asked for their money back tomorr=
ow, the bank wouldn=E2=80=99t have it. But everyone is confident that, if=
=C2=A0<em>they=C2=A0</em>ask for their money back tomorrow, the bank=C2=A0<=
em>will=C2=A0</em>have it. So they mostly don=E2=80=99t ask for it, so=C2=
=A0when they do, the bank=C2=A0<em>does=C2=A0</em>have it.=C2=A0The widespr=
ead belief that banks have the money is=C2=A0<em>what makes it true</em>.</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is obvious=C2=A0stuff.<a class=3D"footnot=
e-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; =
display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a> Also obvious, and famous, is that it is an unstable equilibrium. If pe=
ople stop believing it, it stops being true. If everyone stops believing in=
 a bank, they will all rush to get their money out, and the bank won=E2=80=
=99t have it, and their lack of belief will be retrospectively justified. W=
hereas if they had kept believing, their belief would also have been justif=
ied.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Isn=E2=80=99t this ridiculous? But there is a =
deep social purpose to the=C2=A0confidence trick. Banking is a way for peop=
le collectively to make long-term, risky bets without noticing them, a way =
to pool risks so that everyone is safer and better-off.<a class=3D"footnote=
-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; d=
isplay: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a> You and I put our money in the bank because it is =E2=80=9Cmoney in th=
e bank,=E2=80=9D it=C2=A0is very safe, and=C2=A0we can use it tomorrow to p=
ay rent or buy a sandwich. And then the bank goes around making 30-year fix=
ed-rate mortgage loans: Homeowners=C2=A0could never borrow money from=C2=A0=
<em>me=C2=A0</em>for 30 years, because I might need the money for a sandwic=
h=C2=A0tomorrow, but they can borrow from=C2=A0<em>us collectively=C2=A0</e=
m>because the bank has diversified that liquidity risk among lots of deposi=
tors. Or the bank makes small-business loans to businesses that might go ba=
nkrupt: Those businesses could never borrow from=C2=A0<em>me</em>, because =
I need the money and don=E2=80=99t want to take the risk of losing it, but =
they can borrow from=C2=A0<em>us collectively=C2=A0</em>because the bank ha=
s diversified that credit risk among lots of depositors and also lots of bo=
rrowers.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">All of this is well known and there is a huge =
social apparatus of bank regulation and supervision and backstopping that i=
s all designed to make this work better, to make it=C2=A0<em>safer</em>, to=
=C2=A0boost<em>=C2=A0</em>confidence in banks and to make it more justified=
, to make sure that banks=C2=A0<em>do=C2=A0</em>have enough liquidity=C2=A0=
that if a lot of people ask for money they will get it, that they=C2=A0have=
 enough capital that if they lose money on their loans they=E2=80=99ll stil=
l have enough to pay depositors, that they don=E2=80=99t take dumb=C2=A0ris=
ks with depositors=E2=80=99 money. Actual confidence in banks, in the US in=
 2023, is not just =E2=80=9Cwell I am sure the nice people down at the bank=
 know what they are doing,=E2=80=9D but also some version of =E2=80=9CI am =
sure that the regulators are keeping an eye on the banks, and that the gove=
rnment will try to save the banks if anything goes too wrong, and that the =
government can print dollars so it has the=C2=A0<em>capacity=C2=A0</em>to s=
ave the banks.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the basic problem remains: the confidence =
trick, the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3087425=
5.262423/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS9tb2Rlc3Rwcm9wb3NhbDEvc3RhdHVzLzE2MzQ5Mj=
MwMzk0MDkyMDUyNTE_cz00MyZ0PUpYS2hPdDB0MnJ6M2I4ZEpJTmtKalE/607f07ceef4b8524a=
319a23cB798a2f21" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"=
_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid;=
 background-color: #ccc;">multiple equilibria</a>=C2=A0where trust in banks=
 makes them trustworthy and distrust in banks makes them fail. Bankers and =
bank regulators tend not to talk in these terms, in part because they tend =
to take a more practical view of what they are doing each day but also beca=
use=C2=A0talking about it ruins the magic.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=
=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inli=
ne-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0But they know it in their bones; at a deep level they understand =
that they are creatures of social confidence, and that preserving that conf=
idence is their most important job.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">More specifically they know that if there is a=
 run on a bank, and that bank goes bust and doesn=E2=80=99t pay depositors,=
 then there will be a run on other banks. And they know that the run can st=
art with a bank that is <em>bad</em>, that is undercapitalized and made poo=
r decisions and in some sense deserves to fail, but that it can spread to o=
ther banks that are <em>good</em>. And they=C2=A0know that =E2=80=9Cgood=E2=
=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cbad=E2=80=9D are not really the things that matter: Wha=
t makes a bank good is not just its capital ratios and liquidity position b=
ut also=C2=A0<em>confidence</em>, and however good the ratios it is hard fo=
r a=C2=A0bank to survive a loss of confidence.<a class=3D"footnote-index" h=
ref=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: i=
nline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a> They know that they are all interconnected, that they are players in a=
n essentially social game, and that the goal of the game is not to win but =
to keep playing.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"c=
olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backgro=
und-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a>=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you are in charge of=C2=A0a bank, and=C2=A0=
there is a run on some other bank, and your bank is fine, you might be temp=
ted to put out a public statement saying =E2=80=9Cah, see, that bank was ba=
d, so there was a run, but our bank is good and has no exposure to that ban=
k,=C2=A0so there is no need for a run on us.=E2=80=9D Sometimes that is rig=
ht, the bad bank was idiosyncratically insolvent, and you should just avoid=
 it.=C2=A0But <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3087=
4255.262423/aHR0cHM6Ly9lbi53aWtpcGVkaWEub3JnL3dpa2kvUGFuaWNfb2ZfMTkwNyNKLl9=
QLl9Nb3JnYW4/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb08d7eb3" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" item=
scope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorat=
ion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00000=
0; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> long experience</a=
> teaches that it=E2=80=99s often wrong. The right statement is often =E2=
=80=9Chey everyone, that bank is great, there is no reason for a run, and i=
n fact we are=C2=A0<em>increasing our exposure=C2=A0</em>to that bank, beca=
use=C2=A0<em>we=C2=A0</em>are strong and also because we are confident in t=
hat bank.=E2=80=9D You run toward the fire, because <a href=3D"https://link=
.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30874255.262423/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZ=
XJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMTYvZmlyc3QtcmVwdWJsaWMtdG8tZ2V0LTMw=
LWJpbGxpb24tb2YtYmFuay1kZXBvc2l0cy1pbi1yZXNjdWU_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDMxNzIzX01PTkV=
ZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09Mj=
MwMzE3JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBca5da475" i=
temprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: =
#ccc;"> that=E2=80=99s the only way to=C2=A0put it out</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The biggest US banks pledged $30 billion of fr=
esh cash for First Republic Bank to stem the turmoil that has sent deposito=
rs fleeing from regional banks and shaken the country=E2=80=99s financial s=
ystem.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">JPMorgan Chase &amp; Co., Bank of America Corp=
., Citigroup Inc. and Wells Fargo &amp; Co. will contribute $5 billion of u=
ninsured deposits each, while Goldman Sachs Group Inc. and Morgan Stanley w=
ill kick in $2.5 billion apiece, according to a statement Thursday. Other b=
anks will deposit smaller amounts as part of a plan devised along with US r=
egulators.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThis action by America=E2=80=99s larg=
est banks reflects their confidence in First Republic and in banks of all s=
izes,=E2=80=9D the banks said in their statement. The consortium cited the =
outflows of uninsured deposits at a small number of banks following the col=
lapse of Silicon Valley Bank and Signature Bank.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One rough way to think about this is that, in =
the aftermath of the Silicon Valley Bank failure, <a href=3D"https://link.m=
ail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30874255.262423/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubWFya2V0d2F=
0Y2guY29tL3N0b3J5L3JlZ2lvbmFsLWJhbmtzLWFyZS1zZWVpbmctZmxpZ2h0LW9mLWRlcG9zaX=
RzLXRvLXRvby1iaWctdG8tZmFpbC1tZWdhYmFua3MtZTA3MmRhYTc/607f07ceef4b8524a319a=
23cB678c9d77" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bla=
nk" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-botto=
m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; bac=
kground-color: #ccc;">billions of dollars of deposits</a> have moved out of=
 some regional banks like First Republic, which seem risky, and into megaba=
nks like JPMorgan, which seem safe. So JPMorgan is taking some of those dep=
osits and putting them back into First Republic, in part as a vote of confi=
dence and in part because it has nowhere else to put the deposits and might=
 as well earn a bit of=C2=A0interest lending them to First Republic.<a clas=
s=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-6" style=3D"color: #000000; text-dec=
oration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0=
00000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent =
!important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But I=E2=80=99m not sure that=E2=80=99s all of=
 what=E2=80=99s going on. For one thing, some of the deposits fleeing out o=
f regional banks are going into Treasury bills and government money market =
funds: If you are fleeing your bank because you=E2=80=99re worried about wi=
despread bank failure, fleeing to=C2=A0<em>another bank </em>is not the mos=
t obvious move. And regional banks like PNC Financial Services Group and Tr=
uist Financial Corp. are putting $1 billion of deposits each into First Rep=
ublic, and it=E2=80=99s not obvious to me why <em>they</em> would be huge b=
eneficiaries of outflows from First Republic. Fleeing a regional bank for a=
 too-big-to-fail megabank makes a kind of sense, but fleeing one regional b=
ank for another would be weirder.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But it is a good look, for JPMorgan and Citi b=
ut especially for PNC and Truist, to be the rescuer. The point here is not =
necessarily that JPMorgan and Truist have too much cash lying around and ca=
n plop it into First Republic with no problem. The point here is also to<em=
>=C2=A0signal that=C2=A0JPMorgan and Truist have too much cash lying around=
 and can plop it into First Republic with no problem.=C2=A0</em>This consor=
tium rescue of First Republic is supposed to send a message=C2=A0that First=
 Republic is strong and can survive, but it has the pleasant side effect of=
 sending a message=C2=A0that=C2=A0<em>the rescuing banks</em> are strong an=
d can survive.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Did it work? Oh, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/30874255.262423/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmN=
vbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMTcvZmlyc3QtcmVwdWJsaWMtc2hhcmVzLXJlc3VtZS=
1zbGlkZS1hcy1pbnZlc3RvcnMtYXNzZXNzLWFpZD9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMzE3MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGR=
iZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzAzMTcm=
dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB831a63da" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
 meh</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">First Republic Bank shares tumbled again on Fr=
iday, set for their worst week ever, as sentiment around the lender remaine=
d fragile even after proposals for $30 billion of aid from Wall Street=E2=
=80=99s biggest banks.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Shares of First Republic sank as much as 23% F=
riday, triggering at least one volatility halt, bringing its losses for the=
 week to a record 68%. The drop comes after the bank reported that its borr=
owings from the US Federal Reserve varied from $20 billion to $109 billion =
from March 10 to March 15, said it was suspending dividend payments and dis=
closed a dwindling cash position.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CWe find it difficult to come up with =
a realistic scenario where there=E2=80=99s residual value for First Republi=
c common equity holders,=E2=80=9D Wedbush analyst David Chiaverini wrote in=
 a note to clients. Chiaverini downgraded the stock to neutral, cutting his=
 price target to $5 from $140.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Atlantic Equities John Heagerty also downgrade=
d First Republic to neutral citing =E2=80=9Cunprecedented uncertainty=E2=80=
=9D surrounding the California lender. He said a return to prior leverage r=
atios for the bank =E2=80=9Cmay well necessitate a capital raise.=E2=80=9D<=
/p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the goal here is not really to save First =
Republic common equity holders. The goal is to save confidence in the syste=
m. (=E2=80=9CIts shares fell sharply on Friday morning after the bank had s=
aid it would cancel its dividend on Thursday,=E2=80=9D <a href=3D"https://l=
ink.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30874255.262423/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubnl0aW=
1lcy5jb20vMjAyMy8wMy8xNy9idXNpbmVzcy9kZWFsYm9vay9maXJzdC1yZXB1YmxpYy1yZXNjd=
WUuaHRtbA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6b79f9cf" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsco=
pe=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration=
: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; =
border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> reported the New York=
 Times</a>, which is honestly a funny sentence: If there is any question ab=
out a bank=E2=80=99s ability to pay its depositors, of course it should not=
 pay a dividend to its shareholders!<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#fo=
otnote-7" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border=
-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none=
 !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-bloc=
k;">
<span>[7]</span>
</a>)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Let=E2=80=99s talk about a few contrasts. Sili=
con Valley Bank <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30=
874255.262423/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwM=
jMtMDMtMTAvc3RhcnR1cC1iYW5rLWhhZC1hLXN0YXJ0dXAtYmFuay1ydW4_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDMx=
NzIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXR=
tX3Rlcm09MjMwMzE3JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB=
ef3bc354" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgro=
und-color: #ccc;">  failed last week</a> because, to oversimplify slightly,=
 its interconnected network of tech-startup and venture-capitalist deposito=
rs all worked themselves into a panic and rushed to withdraw money all at o=
nce, then tweeted indignantly about how they were justified in doing that a=
nd how it was all the Fed=E2=80=99s fault. It=C2=A0<em>was=C2=A0</em>indivi=
dually rational for each depositor to take its money out and avoid exposure=
 to SVB, but the collective result was quite bad=C2=A0for SVB and for the b=
anking system and for the VCs and startups themselves. Silicon Valley Bank=
=E2=80=99s Silicon Valley customers, it turned out, were individually ratio=
nal but unable to act cooperatively in a mutually beneficial way; in the pr=
isoners=E2=80=99 dilemma of a bank run, they all chose to defect.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Banking analyst Dan Davies was <a href=3D"http=
s://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30874255.262423/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0d=
GVyLmNvbS9kc3F1YXJlZGRpZ2VzdC9zdGF0dXMvMTYzNjQ2MDg4MzE5Mzc2NTkxMg/607f07cee=
f4b8524a319a23cB4cda26e5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" ta=
rget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; =
border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style=
: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> scathing on Twitter</a>, writing about t=
he First Republic rescue:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When you tell 11 bankers that some=
one is in trouble, seems that they ask "how can we help". Just don't try th=
at with effective altruists eh.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness=
.com/click/30874255.262423/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS9kc3F1YXJlZGRpZ2VzdC9z=
dGF0dXMvMTYzNjQ2MzQ3OTA0NDQxNTQ4OQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB836e91bf" itemp=
rop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color:=
 #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; borde=
r-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc=
;">And</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I would also guess that there was =
no one in that room at the fed saying "well actually running on the bank is=
 the rational thing to do actually"</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ben Thompson was possibly even more scathing <=
a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30874255.262423/aHR=
0cHM6Ly9zdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5jb20vMjAyMy90aGUtZGVhdGgtb2Ytc2lsaWNvbi12YWxsZXktYm=
Fuay8/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB5c7f2612" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> at Stratechery</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I assumed that Silicon Valley broa=
dly was in the business of taking care of their own. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0[But] t=
he bank run that resulted made it clear that everyone, from venture capital=
ists to the startups they advised, were solely concerned about their own we=
lfare, not about the ecosystem as a whole.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Thompson=E2=80=99s argument in that post is th=
at Silicon Valley <em>used to be</em> an=C2=A0iterated game among repeat pl=
ayers: Venture capitalists had long careers and made many investments and w=
ould benefit way more from building a good reputation and helping the overa=
ll startup ecosystem than they would by maximizing their winnings on any on=
e deal. But, he argues, as startup exits and venture funds have gotten bigg=
er, =E2=80=9Csuccess became less about a series of victories and more about=
 going big or going home,=E2=80=9D and that cooperative ethos has weakened.=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is funny to think of tech founders and vent=
ure capitalists as creatures of myopic=C2=A0self-interest, while=C2=A0<em>b=
ank CEOs=C2=A0</em>are the generous altruists, but the point is=C2=A0<em>th=
e bankers don=E2=80=99t have a choice</em>. Banking is a necessarily social=
 business, banks are interconnected, and=C2=A0the best and biggest bank is =
only as good as confidence in the broad banking system. You can=E2=80=99t =
=E2=80=9Cgo big or go home=E2=80=9D; even Jamie Dimon has to care about the=
 health of his less competent competitors. If you blitzscale the best food-=
delivery startup and drive all the other food-delivery startups out of busi=
ness, you win; if you build the best bank and other banks start going out o=
f business, that is a mixed bag, at best,=C2=A0<em>for you</em>.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other contrast I want to point to is=C2=A0=
crypto. Crypto is a social construct like banking, but it is far more=C2=A0=
<em>obviously=C2=A0</em>socially constructed. It=E2=80=99s=C2=A0all just st=
uff that people made up in the last decade or so. It relies even more on co=
nfidence, and that confidence is shakier.=C2=A0When a bunch of crypto firms=
 went bust last summer, Sam Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s crypto exchange FTX, an=
d his crypto trading firm Alameda Research, often ended up rescuing them. B=
ankman-Fried got the nickname =E2=80=9CJPEG Morgan,=E2=80=9D referencing J.=
 Pierpont Morgan=E2=80=99s own habit of rescuing troubled banks to avert pa=
nic. This was, I think, smart of him; it was what a good banker would do.=
=C2=A0Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s own wealth was very highly leveraged to overa=
ll confidence in the crypto ecosystem, so it was better for him to support =
failing competitors =E2=80=94=C2=A0and prop up that confidence =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0than it would be to let them fail. He was in a cooperative confidence ga=
me, and he acted like it.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Of course =E2=80=9Cconfidence game=E2=80=9D is=
 also a=C2=A0<em>bad thing</em>, and FTX and Alameda went bust themselves i=
n November, which puts Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s rescues=C2=A0in a worse ligh=
t: It is good to prop up confidence in a socially beneficial system that ru=
ns on=C2=A0confidence, but bad to prop up confidence in a fraud. And while =
banking is a matter of confidence in a long-standing, deeply socially embed=
ded system that finances lots of people=E2=80=99s real-world houses and bus=
inesses, crypto exchanges are=C2=A0=E2=80=A6=C2=A0not that. If you are a ba=
nk and there is a run on the bank, you will have to sell your mortgage loan=
s and Treasury bonds and whatever, and you will lose money selling them at =
fire-sale prices, and you might become insolvent and deposits might be at r=
isk and the FDIC and the Fed=C2=A0might have to step in. But if you are a c=
rypto bank and there is a run on the bank, you will have to sell=C2=A0<em>s=
ome <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30874255.26242=
3/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTEtMTQvZ=
nR4LXMtYmFsYW5jZS1zaGVldC13YXMtYmFkP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAzMTcyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0=
bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDMxNyZ1dG1=
fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe200250e" itemprop=3D"=
StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  ma=
gic beans you made up</a></em>, and you will sell them=C2=A0<em>for zero do=
llars</em>, and you will become=C2=A0<em>extremely=C2=A0</em>insolvent and =
your customers might get pennies on the dollar, and the FDIC and the Fed wi=
ll absolutely not step in because they are not in the crypto business, but =
federal prosecutors will be very interested.=C2=A0</p>
