<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. seize=
d Silicon Valley Bank last Friday, it did what it generally does, which is =
try to find another bank to buy SVB. The bank had assets (mostly loans and =
bonds) worth about $197 billion as of Dec. 31 (presumably lower as of last =
Friday as it had sold assets to meet its bank run),<a class=3D"footnote-ind=
ex" href=3D"#footnote-8" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !im=
portant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bot=
tom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; displ=
ay: inline-block;">
<span>[8]</span>
</a>=C2=A0plus presumably some franchise value for a buyer who might want t=
o do more business with tech startups and venture capitalists. But there wa=
s some uncertainty there: A lot of SVB=E2=80=99s assets are bonds that are =
pretty liquid but, these days, fairly volatile, and a lot of its assets are=
 weird loans to startups and influencers=C2=A0that another bank might have =
a hard time understanding in a weekend.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile SVB had liabilities as of Dec. 31 co=
nsisting of roughly (1) $8 billion of small deposits insured by the FDIC, (=
2) $15 billion of advances from the Federal Home Loan Bank system, which ar=
e required to be paid back ahead of most other claims=C2=A0and (3) $165 bil=
lion of large deposits that were=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>insured because the=
y were above the FDIC=E2=80=99s insurance cap. That comes to about $188 bil=
lion, again as of Dec. 31; by last Friday the numbers were lower because bi=
llions of dollars of deposits had left in the bank run. Presumably the asse=
ts and liabilities had shrunk by=C2=A0<em>roughly=C2=A0</em>the same amount=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0if $20 billion of deposits went out, then $20 billion of as=
sets were sold to generate the cash =E2=80=94=C2=A0though it would not be s=
urprising if the assets went down a bit faster.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But let=E2=80=99s ignore that and just use the=
 December numbers: $197 billion of assets and $188 billion of more-or-less =
deposit-like claims. Another bank might have looked at those numbers and sa=
id =E2=80=9Chmm, $197 billion of assets plus an exciting franchise, I=E2=80=
=99ll pay $210 billion for that.=E2=80=9D It would write the FDIC a check f=
or $210 billion, the FDIC would pay out $188 billion to depositors and the =
FHLBs, and there=E2=80=99d be money left over for SVB=E2=80=99s bondholders=
 and maybe even shareholders. (I mean, really=C2=A0it would not write a che=
ck to the FDIC, it would just=C2=A0<em>assume the deposits: </em>Depositors=
 would wake up on Monday morning to find that their deposits were now at th=
e acquiring bank and everything was fine.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=
=3D"#footnote-9" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
